kholm: [[Natur & Kultur]], 2015; {{ISBN|978-91-271-3430-0}}. {{in lang|sv}}\n* Capua, Michelangelo \"Anthony Perkins. Prigioniero della Paura.\" Torino, Lindau, 2003; {{ISBN|978-8867082759}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000578}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|20750}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{AllMovie name|106120}}\n* [http://hollywoodgothique.com/perkins.html Psycho star Anthony Perkins on playing Norman Bates]\n* [http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/multimedia/video/2008/wallace/perkins_tony.html Anthony Perkins] interviewed by [[Mike Wallace]] on ''The Mike Wallace Interview'' March 22, 1958\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Anthony Perkins\n| list =\n{{Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation masculine 1960\u20131979}}\n{{David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actor}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Film|LGBT}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Bisexual male actors]]\n[[Category:Brooks School alumni]]\n[[Category:Buckingham Browne & Nichols School alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actor winners]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello winners]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:LGBT directors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Boston]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:New Star of the Year (Actor) Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:People from Wellfleet, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:RCA Victor artists]]\n[[Category:Rollins College alumni]]\n[[Category:Theatre World Award winners]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Perkins"}
{"title_page": "Gladys Leslie", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gladys Leslie\n| image              = Gladys Leslie Photoplay May 1919.jpg\n| imagesize          = 250px\n| caption            = ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]'', 1919\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|3|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1976|10|2|1899|3|5}}\n| death_place        = [[Boynton Beach, Florida]], U.S.\n| birth_name         = \n| spouse             = \n}}\n\n'''Gladys Leslie Moore''' (March 5, 1895 &ndash; October 2, 1976) was an [[United States|American]] actress in [[silent film]], active in the 1910s and 1920s.  Though less-remembered than superstars like [[Mary Pickford]], she had a number of starring roles from 1917 to the early 1920s and was one of the young female stars of her day.\n\n==Film career==\n[[File:The Wooing of Princess Pat 1918.jpg|thumb|[[Film still|Still]] of Leslie in the Vitagraph release ''The Wooing of Princess Pat'' (1918)]]\nLeslie began her movie career around 1915, acting in [[short film]]s produced by the [[Edison Studios|Edison Company]].  By 1917, she was making films with the [[Thanhouser Company]] in [[New Rochelle, New York]], including ''The Vicar of Wakefield'' (1917).  The ''[[New York Herald]]'''s review of that film dubbed her the \"Girl With A Million Dollar Smile,\" and caused studio head [[Edwin Thanhouser]] to decide she was ready for leading roles.<ref name=\"smile1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TAlkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vHoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3356,1179512|title=Florence LaBadie, Irresistible Star, \"When Love Was Blind\"|last=|first=|date=12 May 1917|work=Calgary Daily Herald|access-date=}}</ref>  Soon she was starring in the lead role in 1917's ''[[An Amateur Orphan]]'', but was quickly wooed over to [[Vitagraph Studios]] and starred in a number of Vitagraph releases in 1918 and 1919.  Leslie and another young female Vitagraph star, [[Bessie Love]], starred in numerous films in young girl-type roles that were popular at the time.<ref name=\"juvie1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8EoPAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&q=%22gladys+leslie%22#search_anchor|title=The Big V: A History of the Vitagraph Company|last=Slide|first=Anthony|date=|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=1987|isbn=9780810820302|location=|pages=90\u201391|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"munsey1\">Bennett, Whitman (June 1920). [https://books.google.com/books?id=vIvNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA101&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&hl=en&ei=WWByTofmEMLW0QGahpTpCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwADgU#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22&f=false The Artistic Influence of the Motion Picture], ''[[Munsey's Magazine]]'' (photo of Leslie)</ref><ref name=\"clark1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/margueriteclarka00nunn|url-access=registration|quote=gladys leslie First National Pictures.|title=Marguerite Clark, America's Darling of Broadway and the Silent Screen|last=Nunn|first=William Curtis|date=1981|publisher=TCU Press|year=|isbn=9780912646695|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/margueriteclarka00nunn/page/100 100]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"stpete1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WxFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v0wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7028,7639257&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en|title=News Notes From Movieland|last=Dean|first=Daisy|date=21 December 1922|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"stpete2\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vQ9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=n0wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7196,115301&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en|title=At The Theaters|last=|first=|date=18 February 1926|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=}}</ref>  Leslie's similar appearance to [[Mary Pickford]] was also often noted.<ref name=\"photo1918-1\">{{Cite magazine|last=Howe|first=Herbert|date=July 1918|title=A Truly Ingenuous Ingenue|url=|magazine=[[Photoplay]]|page=27|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLeslie's association with Vitagraph ended by 1920 and she continued to make films with a number of different studios.  Her first non-Vitagraph picture in 1920 was ''[[A Child for Sale]]'', directed by [[Ivan Abramson]], where she played a starring role.<ref name=\"nytimesendvita\">(18 January 1920). [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/01/18/112645997.pdf Picture Plays and People], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (\"Gladys Leslie, who recently finished the term of her contract with Vitagraph, has signed up to star in a picture to be directed by Ivan Abramson.\") (film was \"A Child for Sale\")</ref><ref name=\"vitaoverphoto\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=634NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA16-IA85&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+moore&hl=en&ei=8F5yTvDXEaPu0gHV69iUCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20moore&f=false Questions and Answers], ''[[Photoplay]]'' (June 1920), p. 113 (reporting in response to a fan question that Leslie was no longer with Vitagraph, and had recently made a picture with [[Ivan Abramson]], which would have been 1920's ''[[A Child for Sale]]'')</ref> And in 1923, she had the lead female role in ''[[Haldane of the Secret Service]]'' featuring [[Harry Houdini]].  Nevertheless, her share of starring roles started to decline, and her last appearance was in 1925.  She had always claimed, however, that she would stop making films when her bank account \"has mounted high enough.\"<ref name=\"rovi\">Wollstein, Hans J. [http://www.allrovi.com/name/gladys-leslie-p41959 Gladys Leslie - Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130116193802/http://www.allrovi.com/name/gladys-leslie-p41959 |date=2013-01-16 }}, ''[[AllRovi]]'', Retrieved September 19, 2011</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nLeslie was born in [[New York City]] on March 5, 1899, and she died in [[Boynton Beach, Florida]] on October 2, 1976 at age 77.<ref name=\"necro\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J5ZZAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Gladys+Leslie%22+silent+film&q=%22Gladys+Leslie%22#search_anchor|title=Silent film necrology: births and deaths of over 9000 performers, directors, producers, and other filmmakers of the silent era, through 1993|last=Vazzana|first=Eugene Michael|date=May 1995|publisher=McFarland|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=195|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the new trend of actors doing product endorsements in the early 1920s, Leslie appeared in ads for Tokio Beauty Cream, which was claimed to have given her \"magnetic personality.\"<ref name=\"ads\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f4beond0wMwC&pg=PA52&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+pickford#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20pickford&f=false|title=Movie Crazy: Fans, Stars, and the Cult of Celebrity|last=Barbas|first=Samantha|date=2002-10-18|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=|isbn=9781403960450|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref> She also wore blouses by [[Edith Varian Cockcroft]] in clothing ads.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=28 January 1922|title=Derby Velvet|url=|journal=Dry Goods Economist|volume=76|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n[[File:Miss Dulcie From Dixie.jpg|thumb|''[[Miss Dulcie from Dixie]]'' (1919)]]\n[[File:Gladys Leslie - Aug 1921 Photoplay.jpg|thumb|Leslie, 1921]]\n* ''[[Ranson's Folly (1915 film)|Ranson's Folly]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Vicar of Wakefield (1917 film)|The Vicar of Wakefield]]'' as Sophia Primrose (Thanhouser, 1917) (starring [[Frederick Warde]])<ref name=\"vicar\">[http://www.thanhouser.org/films/Vicar-1917.htm The Vicar of Wakefield] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223122943/http://www.thanhouser.org/films/Vicar-1917.htm |date=2017-02-23 }}, Thanhouser.org (full movie available online), Retrieved September 16, 2011</ref>\n* ''[[An Amateur Orphan]]'' as Marcia Schuyler (Thanhouser, 1917)\n* ''[[When Love Was Blind (1917 film)|When Love Was Blind]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[Her Beloved Enemy]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[It Happened to Adele]]'' as Adele ([[Thanhouser Company|Thanhouser]], 1917)\n* ''His Own People'' as Molly Conway (Vitagraph, 1917) (co-starring [[Harry T. Morey]])<ref name=\"ownpeople\">Langman, Larry. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ltcNWzVEaEUC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+%22his+own+people%22&source=bl&ots=YMgu6E-EiN&sig=JkrmzhHgyANniehw6qk6GCiP8iY&hl=en&ei=EUxzTuKFJovE0AHr0fjFDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFYQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20%22his%20own%20people%22&f=false American film cycles: the silent era], p.152 (1998) (summary of plot of ''His Own People'')</ref><ref name=\"ireland3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3Y1ZAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&q=%22gladys+leslie%22#search_anchor|title=The cinema and Ireland|last=Slide|first=Anthony|date=1988|publisher=McFarland & Company Incorporated Pub|year=|isbn=9780899503226|location=|pages=104|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''The Wooing of Princess Pat'' as Princess Pat (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Little Miss No-Account'' as Patty Baring (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Little Runaway'' as Ann Acushla (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Soap Girl'' as Marjorie Sanford (Vitagraph, 1918)<ref name=\"soap1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1n0NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA121-IA72&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20vitagraph&f=false|title=Photoplay: The Aristocrat of Motion Picture Magazines|last=|first=|date=1917|publisher=Photoplay Magazine Publishing Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=79|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''[[Wild Primrose]]'' as Primrose Standish (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Nymph of the Foothills'' as Emma Chaney (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Mating'' as Nancy Fanne (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Beloved Impostor'' as Betty (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Fortune's Child'' (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''[[Miss Dulcie from Dixie]]'' as Dulcie Culpepper (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''A Stitch in Time'' as Phoebe Ann (Vitagraph, 1919, directed by [[Ralph Ince]])\n* ''The Adventure Shop'' (1919)\n* ''Too Many Crooks'' as Boston Fanny (Vitagraph, 1919, directed by [[Ralph Ince]])\n* ''The Girl-Woman'' as Belinda (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''[[The Gray Towers Mystery]]'' as June Wheeler (Vitagraph, 1919)<ref>(14 October 1919). [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/738552112.html?dids=738552112:738552112&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+14%2C+1919&author=&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=GIRL+FIGHTS+FOR+FORTUNE+LEFT+HER&pqatl=google Girl Fights For Fortune Left Her], ''Hartford Courant'' (\"Miss Gladys Leslie is a very attractive young heiress in \"Gray Towers Mystery,\" the Vitagraph picture at the Princess Theater the first half of the week. The story is that of a young girl who inherits a fortune from her uncle but is forced to fight for it ...\")</ref> \n* ''[[A Child for Sale]]'' (Graphic Films, 1920)\n* ''The Midnight Bride'' (Vitagraph, 1920)\n* ''[[Straight Is the Way (1921 film)|Straight is the Way]]'' (Cosmopolitan, 1921) (starring [[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]])\n* ''[[Jim the Penman (1921 film)|Jim the Penman]]'' (1921) (starring [[Lionel Barrymore]])<ref name=\"penman1\">\n(10 April 1921) [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-04-10/ed-1/seq-63/ Gladys Leslie], ''New York Tribune'' (brief)</ref>\n* ''[[God's Country and the Law]]'' (1921) \n* ''[[Timothy's Quest]]'' (1922)<ref name=\"quest11\">(28 June 1923). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QAdIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ws4MAAAAIBAJ&pg=4661,3823843&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en \"Timothy's Quest\" To Open At Grand Today], ''Dubuque Telegraph-Herald''</ref>\n*''[[The Darling of the Rich]]''  (1922)\n* ''[[The Snitching Hour]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[If Winter Comes (1923 film)|If Winter Comes]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Man and Wife (film)|Man and Wife]]'' (1923) (with [[Maurice Costello]])\n* ''[[Haldane of the Secret Service]]'' (1923) (with [[Harry Houdini]])\n* ''Enemies of Youth'' (1925) (with [[Mahlon Hamilton]])\n* ''Pearl of Love'' (1925) (with [[Betty Balfour]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0504109}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170223122943/http://www.thanhouser.org/films/Vicar-1917.htm The Vicar of Wakefield (1917)], full movie online at Thanhouser.org\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leslie, Gladys}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gladys Leslie\n| image              = Gladys Leslie Photoplay May 1919.jpg\n| imagesize          = 250px\n| caption            = ''[[Motion Picture Magazine]]'', 1919\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|3|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1976|10|2|1899|3|5}}\n| death_place        = [[Boynton Beach, Florida]], U.S.\n| birth_name         = \n| spouse             = \n}}\n\n'''Gladys Leslie Moore''' (March 5, 1895 &ndash; October 2, 1976) was an [[United States|American]] actress in [[silent film]], active in the 1910s and 1920s.  Though less-remembered than superstars like [[Mary Pickford]], she had a number of starring roles from 1917 to the early 1920s and was one of the young female stars of her day.\n\n==Film career==\n[[File:The Wooing of Princess Pat 1918.jpg|thumb|[[Film still|Still]] of Leslie in the Vitagraph release ''The Wooing of Princess Pat'' (1918)]]\nLeslie began her movie career around 1915, acting in [[short film]]s produced by the [[Edison Studios|Edison Company]].  By 1917, she was making films with the [[Thanhouser Company]] in [[New Rochelle, New York]], including ''The Vicar of Wakefield'' (1917).  The ''[[New York Herald]]'''s review of that film dubbed her the \"Girl With A Million Dollar Smile,\" and caused studio head [[Edwin Thanhouser]] to decide she was ready for leading roles.<ref name=\"smile1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TAlkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vHoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3356,1179512|title=Florence LaBadie, Irresistible Star, \"When Love Was Blind\"|last=|first=|date=12 May 1917|work=Calgary Daily Herald|access-date=}}</ref>  Soon she was starring in the lead role in 1917's ''[[An Amateur Orphan]]'', but was quickly wooed over to [[Vitagraph Studios]] and starred in a number of Vitagraph releases in 1918 and 1919.  Leslie and another young female Vitagraph star, [[Bessie Love]], starred in numerous films in young girl-type roles that were popular at the time.<ref name=\"juvie1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8EoPAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&q=%22gladys+leslie%22#search_anchor|title=The Big V: A History of the Vitagraph Company|last=Slide|first=Anthony|date=|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=1987|isbn=9780810820302|location=|pages=90\u201391|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"munsey1\">Bennett, Whitman (June 1920). [https://books.google.com/books?id=vIvNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA101&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&hl=en&ei=WWByTofmEMLW0QGahpTpCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwADgU#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22&f=false The Artistic Influence of the Motion Picture], ''[[Munsey's Magazine]]'' (photo of Leslie)</ref><ref name=\"clark1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/margueriteclarka00nunn|url-access=registration|quote=gladys leslie First National Pictures.|title=Marguerite Clark, America's Darling of Broadway and the Silent Screen|last=Nunn|first=William Curtis|date=1981|publisher=TCU Press|year=|isbn=9780912646695|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/margueriteclarka00nunn/page/100 100]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"stpete1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WxFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=v0wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7028,7639257&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en|title=News Notes From Movieland|last=Dean|first=Daisy|date=21 December 1922|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"stpete2\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vQ9PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=n0wDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7196,115301&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en|title=At The Theaters|last=|first=|date=18 February 1926|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=}}</ref>  Leslie's similar appearance to [[Mary Pickford]] was also often noted.<ref name=\"photo1918-1\">{{Cite magazine|last=Howe|first=Herbert|date=July 1918|title=A Truly Ingenuous Ingenue|url=|magazine=[[Photoplay]]|page=27|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLeslie's association with Vitagraph ended by 1920 and she continued to make films with a number of different studios.  Her first non-Vitagraph picture in 1920 was ''[[A Child for Sale]]'', directed by [[Ivan Abramson]], where she played a starring role.<ref name=\"nytimesendvita\">(18 January 1920). [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/01/18/112645997.pdf Picture Plays and People], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (\"Gladys Leslie, who recently finished the term of her contract with Vitagraph, has signed up to star in a picture to be directed by Ivan Abramson.\") (film was \"A Child for Sale\")</ref><ref name=\"vitaoverphoto\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=634NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA16-IA85&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+moore&hl=en&ei=8F5yTvDXEaPu0gHV69iUCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20moore&f=false Questions and Answers], ''[[Photoplay]]'' (June 1920), p. 113 (reporting in response to a fan question that Leslie was no longer with Vitagraph, and had recently made a picture with [[Ivan Abramson]], which would have been 1920's ''[[A Child for Sale]]'')</ref> And in 1923, she had the lead female role in ''[[Haldane of the Secret Service]]'' featuring [[Harry Houdini]].  Nevertheless, her share of starring roles started to decline, and her last appearance was in 1925.  She had always claimed, however, that she would stop making films when her bank account \"has mounted high enough.\"<ref name=\"rovi\">Wollstein, Hans J. [http://www.allrovi.com/name/gladys-leslie-p41959 Gladys Leslie - Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130116193802/http://www.allrovi.com/name/gladys-leslie-p41959 |date=2013-01-16 }}, ''[[AllRovi]]'', Retrieved September 19, 2011</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nLeslie was born in [[New York City]] on March 5, 1899, and she died in [[Boynton Beach, Florida]] on October 2, 1976 at age 77.<ref name=\"necro\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J5ZZAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Gladys+Leslie%22+silent+film&q=%22Gladys+Leslie%22#search_anchor|title=Silent film necrology: births and deaths of over 9000 performers, directors, producers, and other filmmakers of the silent era, through 1993|last=Vazzana|first=Eugene Michael|date=May 1995|publisher=McFarland|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=195|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the new trend of actors doing product endorsements in the early 1920s, Leslie appeared in ads for Tokio Beauty Cream, which was claimed to have given her \"magnetic personality.\"<ref name=\"ads\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=f4beond0wMwC&pg=PA52&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+pickford#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20pickford&f=false|title=Movie Crazy: Fans, Stars, and the Cult of Celebrity|last=Barbas|first=Samantha|date=2002-10-18|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=|isbn=9781403960450|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref> She also wore blouses by [[Edith Varian Cockcroft]] in clothing ads.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=28 January 1922|title=Derby Velvet|url=|journal=Dry Goods Economist|volume=76|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n[[File:Miss Dulcie From Dixie.jpg|thumb|''[[Miss Dulcie from Dixie]]'' (1919)]]\n[[File:Gladys Leslie - Aug 1921 Photoplay.jpg|thumb|Leslie, 1921]]\n* ''[[Ranson's Folly (1915 film)|Ranson's Folly]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Vicar of Wakefield (1917 film)|The Vicar of Wakefield]]'' as Sophia Primrose (Thanhouser, 1917) (starring [[Frederick Warde]])<ref name=\"vicar\">[http://www.thanhouser.org/films/Vicar-1917.htm The Vicar of Wakefield] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223122943/http://www.thanhouser.org/films/Vicar-1917.htm |date=2017-02-23 }}, Thanhouser.org (full movie available online), Retrieved September 16, 2011</ref>\n* ''[[An Amateur Orphan]]'' as Marcia Schuyler (Thanhouser, 1917)\n* ''[[When Love Was Blind (1917 film)|When Love Was Blind]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[Her Beloved Enemy]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[It Happened to Adele]]'' as Adele ([[Thanhouser Company|Thanhouser]], 1917)\n* ''His Own People'' as Molly Conway (Vitagraph, 1917) (co-starring [[Harry T. Morey]])<ref name=\"ownpeople\">Langman, Larry. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ltcNWzVEaEUC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+%22his+own+people%22&source=bl&ots=YMgu6E-EiN&sig=JkrmzhHgyANniehw6qk6GCiP8iY&hl=en&ei=EUxzTuKFJovE0AHr0fjFDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CFYQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20%22his%20own%20people%22&f=false American film cycles: the silent era], p.152 (1998) (summary of plot of ''His Own People'')</ref><ref name=\"ireland3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3Y1ZAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph&q=%22gladys+leslie%22#search_anchor|title=The cinema and Ireland|last=Slide|first=Anthony|date=1988|publisher=McFarland & Company Incorporated Pub|year=|isbn=9780899503226|location=|pages=104|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''The Wooing of Princess Pat'' as Princess Pat (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Little Miss No-Account'' as Patty Baring (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Little Runaway'' as Ann Acushla (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Soap Girl'' as Marjorie Sanford (Vitagraph, 1918)<ref name=\"soap1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1n0NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA121-IA72&dq=%22gladys+leslie%22+vitagraph#v=onepage&q=%22gladys%20leslie%22%20vitagraph&f=false|title=Photoplay: The Aristocrat of Motion Picture Magazines|last=|first=|date=1917|publisher=Photoplay Magazine Publishing Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=79|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''[[Wild Primrose]]'' as Primrose Standish (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Nymph of the Foothills'' as Emma Chaney (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Mating'' as Nancy Fanne (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''The Beloved Impostor'' as Betty (Vitagraph, 1918)\n* ''Fortune's Child'' (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''[[Miss Dulcie from Dixie]]'' as Dulcie Culpepper (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''A Stitch in Time'' as Phoebe Ann (Vitagraph, 1919, directed by [[Ralph Ince]])\n* ''The Adventure Shop'' (1919)\n* ''Too Many Crooks'' as Boston Fanny (Vitagraph, 1919, directed by [[Ralph Ince]])\n* ''The Girl-Woman'' as Belinda (Vitagraph, 1919)\n* ''[[The Gray Towers Mystery]]'' as June Wheeler (Vitagraph, 1919)<ref>(14 October 1919). [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/738552112.html?dids=738552112:738552112&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+14%2C+1919&author=&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=GIRL+FIGHTS+FOR+FORTUNE+LEFT+HER&pqatl=google Girl Fights For Fortune Left Her], ''Hartford Courant'' (\"Miss Gladys Leslie is a very attractive young heiress in \"Gray Towers Mystery,\" the Vitagraph picture at the Princess Theater the first half of the week. The story is that of a young girl who inherits a fortune from her uncle but is forced to fight for it ...\")</ref> \n* ''[[A Child for Sale]]'' (Graphic Films, 1920)\n* ''The Midnight Bride'' (Vitagraph, 1920)\n* ''[[Straight Is the Way (1921 film)|Straight is the Way]]'' (Cosmopolitan, 1921) (starring [[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]])\n* ''[[Jim the Penman (1921 film)|Jim the Penman]]'' (1921) (starring [[Lionel Barrymore]])<ref name=\"penman1\">\n(10 April 1921) [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-04-10/ed-1/seq-63/ Gladys Leslie], ''New York Tribune'' (brief)</ref>\n* ''[[God's Country and the Law]]'' (1921) \n* ''[[Timothy's Quest]]'' (1922)<ref name=\"quest11\">(28 June 1923). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QAdIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ws4MAAAAIBAJ&pg=4661,3823843&dq=gladys-leslie&hl=en \"Timothy's Quest\" To Open At Grand Today], ''Dubuque Telegraph-Herald''</ref>\n*''[[The Darling of the Rich]]''  (1922)\n* ''[[The Snitching Hour]]'' (1922)\n*